---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
import TokenizerExplorer from '../../components/interactive/TokenizerExplorer';
---

<BaseLayout title="Vocabulary and Token IDs">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L03" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What is a vocabulary ID?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        The model's vocabulary is a finite table. Every possible token piece has a unique integer ID.
      </p>
      <p>
        When text is tokenized, each piece is looked up in this table to find its ID. The model's actual input is a sequence of these integers — not strings.
      </p>
      <p>
        The vocabulary size (often written <code>|V|</code>) is fixed when the model is trained. A typical vocabulary has 32,000 to 256,000 entries.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Interactive — Tokenizer Explorer</div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
        Look at the Token IDs section below. Each token piece maps to a specific integer.
      </p>
      <TokenizerExplorer client:load />
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Vocabulary lookup for "The cat sat":
        </p>
        <table style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom: var(--border-default);">
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--space-2); color: var(--ink-ghost); font-weight: 400; font-size: var(--text-xs); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase;">Token piece</th>
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--space-2); color: var(--ink-ghost); font-weight: 400; font-size: var(--text-xs); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase;">Token ID</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td style="padding: var(--space-2); color: var(--sem-token);">"The"</td><td style="padding: var(--space-2);">791</td></tr>
            <tr><td style="padding: var(--space-2); color: var(--sem-token);">" cat"</td><td style="padding: var(--space-2);">2368</td></tr>
            <tr><td style="padding: var(--space-2); color: var(--sem-token);">" sat"</td><td style="padding: var(--space-2);">3290</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          The model receives <code>[791, 2368, 3290]</code> — three integers, nothing else.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Vocabulary: a table of |V| entries</div>
        <div>Token IDs: [n_tokens] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(a 1D sequence of integers)</span></div>
        <div>Each ID &#x2208; &#x7b;0, 1, ..., |V|-1&#x7d;</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>The new concept is <strong>indexing into a finite table</strong>:</p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--sem-token); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0; display: inline-block;">
        vocab[id] → token_piece
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
        The vocabulary is just a lookup table. Given an ID, you get the corresponding text piece. Given a text piece, you get the ID.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, the vocabulary is loaded from the model file. The tokenizer uses it to convert text to IDs and IDs back to text.
          The model weights include an embedding table that maps each ID to a learned vector.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Vocabulary size |V| determines the size of the output layer (one score per entry). Larger vocabularies mean more work at the output head.
          This is why vocabulary size is a design decision, not just a data detail.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L03"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L03-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'What does the model see as input?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Unicode strings', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Integer token IDs', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Probability distributions', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The model receives a sequence of integer IDs. All text processing happens before the model runs.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L03-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'If the vocabulary has 32,000 entries, what is the range of valid token IDs?',
            tag: 'math',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: '1 to 32,000', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: '0 to 31,999', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: '0 to 32,000', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'With |V| = 32,000 entries, IDs range from 0 to 31,999 (zero-indexed).',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
